{"title":"DReSD: Dense Retrieval for Speculative Decoding","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Sparse retrieval-based speculative decoding drafts next tokens by exact string matching over short contexts, which lowers precision/recall and limits acceptance rates and speed gains.","method":"DReSD replaces sparse matching with dense, semantic retrieval: it queries a static key–value datastore using the LLM’s current state (last hidden state before the LM head) as a contextualised token embedding, then retrieves next-token sequences via approximate nearest neighbour search (ScaNN) with cosine similarity. To make this efficient and accurate, DReSD applies dual normalisation (z-score on full embeddings and Lp magnitude normalisation post-PCA) and dimensionality reduction (PCA to 64 dims) before search, and filters candidates to those beginning with the LLM’s own next-token prediction. Drafts are verified with exact, batched SD verification, preserving the LLM’s outputs. Across experiments, DReSD achieves on average 87% higher acceptance rates, 65% longer accepted token runs, and 19% faster generation than sparse REST, with up to 4.64x speedup over autoregressive decoding."},{"problem":"Naively deploying dense retrieval for SD can be slow or ineffective without the right design choices; it is unclear which factors most impact acceptance and throughput.","method":"The paper identifies three critical factors and provides concrete configurations: (1) Embedding preprocessing—z-score normalisation, PCA to 64 dimensions (capturing ~30–40% variance), and post-PCA normalisation—yields high retrieval quality (MRR ~93–94) and better SD than higher dims, while avoiding large-vector overheads. (2) Datastore alignment—prompt, response, and sampling alignment—matters multiplicatively: using in-distribution (ID) datastores built from the target LLM’s own responses raises MAR by ~70% on CodeAlpaca despite ~40% fewer tokens; matching sampling (e.g., greedy datastore with greedy decoding) further improves speedups. (3) Draft shape—tuning the number vs. length of drafts—is key: narrow-and-deep drafts for greedy (e.g., 3×20) and more, shorter drafts for nucleus (e.g., 10×10) outperform REST’s fixed shallow–wide trees, yielding 10–23% (nucleus) and 42–218% (greedy) faster speeds over REST and enabling up to 4.64x average speedups over autoregressive generation."}]}
